article.description:
Epiphanny Prince scored 15 points to 
lead No. 6 Rutgers to a 58-50 victory over St. John's on Saturday.
article.headline: Prince gets 15 to lift No. 6 Rutgers by St. John's in Big East opener
article.linkText: Prince propels No. 6 Rutgers to sixth straight win
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) --  Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer was disgusted with her team, even after a victory in the Big East opener.

Epiphanny Prince scored 15 points to lead No. 6 Rutgers to a 58-50 win over St. John's on Saturday night.

"It was a win and let's leave it at that," Stringer said. "We didn't play well."

There was no celebrating in the locker room for Rutgers (11-2), which won its season-high sixth straight game and improved to 7-0 in Big East openers at home.

"We know we didn't play like the Scarlet Knights play and that's defending whether it's inside the paint, from the midrange area, or defending the 3," said Essence Carson, who added 13 points.

Carson, recovering from a stress fracture in her foot, came off the bench for the second straight game. The senior was sidelined for three weeks with the injury, but only missed two games as Rutgers had an extended break for exams.

Stringer didn't play senior Matee Ajavon to rest her weary legs. Ajavon is the team's second leading scorer averaging 11.0 points.

"Her legs are tired so she just needed to get them strengthened," Stringer said. "No matter what she wasn't going to play."

Monique McLean scored 13 points and Sky Lindsay added 11 to lead St. John's (9-5).

Kia Wright scored nine points and had nine assists for the Red Storm. She moved into sixth place on St. John's all-time scoring list, passing Jackie Smith, who finished her career with 1,298 points.

"When Kia Wright is playing up to her capability she's one of the best point guards in the country," St. John's coach Kim Barnes Arico said.

With Rutgers leading 36-35 midway through the second half, the Scarlet Knights went on a 9-0 run to extend the advantage to 10. Prince capped the spurt with a jumper from the top of the key.

St. John's would come no closer than five the rest of the game. During the run, Red Storm center Recee Mitchell went down grabbing her knee after committing a foul. She was helped back to the locker room and didn't return. Mitchell was set to have an MRI on Sunday.

The Red Storm were looking to knock off their first Top 25 team this season.

"It would be nice to get one of these," Barnes Arico said. "We had the lead most of the first half. Down at the end of the game we got a little tight."

The Red Storm were coming off a 97-56 win over Morgan State on Dec. 30. It was St. John's highest scoring effort since Dec. 22, 1994. The Red Storm made a school record 14 3-pointers against Morgan State.

On Saturday, they had a much tougher time against Rutgers.

Early on the Red Storm held a one-point lead before going on a 8-0 run to extend the advantage to 14-5 with 13:02 left in the first half.

Rutgers responded holding St. John's scoreless over the next 5 minutes to close to 14-12 on Rashidat Junaid's layup. Kelly McManmon ended the Red Storm's drought with a 3-pointer to extend the lead back to five before Rutgers closed the half on a 14-6 run to take a 26-23 advantage at the break.

Carson scored eight points and Prince had the other six during the closing spurt. The two combined for 19 of Rutgers' 26 points in the first half.

"We came out a little sluggish," Carson said. "We dug ourselves a hole and worked so hard to get out of it. We didn't play like the Scarlet Knights. We weren't hitting free throws and this was just a bad night from there. We'll take the win."

Prince had a rough night from the foul line going 0-for-7. She was shooting 78 percent from the line for her career. The Scarlet Knights were just 6-for-18 from the line in the game.

"I'm pretty disappointed in myself, but at the same time I have to let it go," said Prince of her free throw woes. "Hopefully it will show up better in the next game."

Rutgers has won 17 straight over St. John's and leads the all-time series 30-3.
